full_text:
The amount of money laundered through AdTech/apps/ad exchanges is highly correlated with volume of synthetic diamonds entering the market any a given time, which is highly correlated to the price of natural diamonds. Every incremental synthetic diamond entering the market reduces the value of every incremental natural diamond entering the market.

Why is this important?

The diamond market is fixed by Israelis, who also manage what's called the "Kimberly Scheme" - a certification process that regulates trade in rough diamonds, ostensibly set up to limit the amount of "blood diamonds" circulating in the market.

While the Ramat Gan exchange in Israel is the clearinghouse, plenty of money launders of all stripes and backgrounds use the high vig Israeli cut diamond market (about 25% of Israel's exports, by the way) to launder money, but this is a contracting business model as synthetic diamonds are taking over much of this market.

It's simply becoming harder and harder to launder money through the diamond trade, with worse volumes and higher vigs.

Plus, there are a ton of diamonds held by Boomers (obviously as engagement ring jewelry, but just in general) and as these people die off, more and more already-cut diamonds will re-enter the market, further driving down the cost efficiency of laundering money through the diamond cutting trade.

---

So if you've got a ton of money to launder, what you do now is you clear this through AdTech.

You set up entities on both sides of the market - you buy ad space from one entity located somewhere in the world, you set up digital property on the other side to host these ads - a site or app or whatever, and you have a bot network set up to run up impressions and play pricing on an ad exchange.

The middlemen here are these AdTech companies that turn a blind eye to this (to give them the most credit... some do actively participate).

Now if you're money laundering what you also may wish to do is buy equity (stock) in these middlemen who are making all these great transactions and facilitating transfers. Now you're legally making money off the volume of money laundering you and others are doing.

If you wish to understand app data, ad data, bot networks, simply start with how much diamond marketshare is being taken over by synthetic diamonds and how many already-cut diamonds re-enter the supply chain as estates are liquidated as Boomers die off.

I can't take any AdTech analyst seriously if they don't also track how much allocation is moving out of the diamond trade and into AdTech.

If you want to test who is very smart vs. not smart, here's what you do. It's called The Restaurant Test.

You go out to a restaurant with the person you're testing and you ask the person to tell you what dialogue is happening at the next table over.

You look over. It could be a first date. A business meeting. Whatever.

You say to the person you're testing to play out what dialogue is happening over there.

Make sense?

Then comes the real test, now that you've established characters and dialogue for the next table over. 

You ask the person you're testing to now pretend the next table is making dialogue about next table over from them.

Now that we at Table A have played out a little joke between us about what is going on at Table B, what dialogue is happening at Table B about Table C? If Table B is playing the game we're playing at Table A but about Table C, what is that conversation like?

Only the highly intelligent can figure out how to answer this and play it out in a way that makes any sense.

Huge alpha.

The relational database (1970s) is what allows for securitization, underpins software, and is why post-Bretton Woods ethnic minorities and women could open credit lines in the US without, frankly, a white male co-signer. The relational database is what allows "scoring" of individuals, entities, etc. in a way more robust than saying, "Gee this guy seems like he'll pay me back so I'll lend him some money."

When IBM researcher Edgar F. Codd published a paper in 1970 titled "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks" that theorized the relational database model, we kicked off modern finance.

By being able to price nearly 100% of an adult population and lend to it based on data instead of lending to ~40% of a population based on handshakes, we created modern finance in the US and the floating US dollar became the world's reserve currency.

Plus, at this time women began to go to college en masse instead of just normal schools (teaching colleges) or nursing schools. They took these college educations and began working in white collar jobs where they'd input data into relational databases, extract data from relational databases, analyze data in relational databases, etc. and all of this made it possible to take on larger amounts of loans and for consumer lending products to become more complex.

I'm not sure we've actually entered a Sixth Phase yet. The relational database is still going too strong.

What is the bull case on Veradigm $MDRX? Chuck Myers lands the plane?

The key to understanding a Veradigm bull case may lie in Science dot io's API documentation.

$MDRX bought Science dot io during an "AI hype" phase, yet Science dot io's API documentation shows that this project is more or less an undergrad CS 101 text scraping project with a social media thinkfluencer slapped on top.

The main problem here is that Science dot io positioned itself as a way to "automate" or streamline PHI and health data by pulling data and classifying it out of text entries. Yet on the API docs we can see that the advertised accuracy for fields/keys like "Medical Record" or "Phone" have only 83% and 84% accuracy respectively.

The reason EHR record/medical data processing is so manual in general is because this requires precision AND accuracy.

This silly nonsense adds a problem. Now you have two problems: the problem that it takes a while to manually validate EHR data + you bought a new solution to automate the first problem but it doesn't work very well. In some cases, you may have three problems is you had to hire an engineer to fiddle with Science dot io, and you've implemented a new solution, and none of this is accurate enough to solve your original time problem.

I don't know who is going to be picking up this bag. full_text:
Love Concord, MA area. If you want a fun day trip for you and family here's what you do:

1/ You visit a book store like the one below and you buy a book off this shelf.

2/ You visit Sleepy Hollow Cemetery in Concord and you spend an hour in reflection of the accomplishments of the people buried there. Take a walk around. It's open to the public.

They have everyone in this cemetery from the guy who directed the original Star Trek and I Love Lucy to Ralph Waldo Emerson to Louisa May Alcott to war heroes like "Moose" Heyliger from the 101st Airborne Easy Company, which folks may know from the Band of Brothers mini-series program.

Pull up an old Star Trek or I Love Lucy on your phone and watch it as you stand next to the grave of the guy who made that, who is buried in the ground a stone's throw away from Ralph Waldo Emerson.

3/ Then, you read a passage from the book you just bought next to the grave of the writer who wrote those words. You can read this out loud or you can just read it quietly.

How cool is this? You're reading the words of a famous author from 100+ years ago who had something to say about something and you're reading that dead person's thoughts over that dead person's grave. What an honor!

4/ Next, you visit Minuteman National Park right down the street, which has the Old North Bridge, where the American Revolution commenced. You walk over the bridge and you read the plaques and you think about what it was like for a bunch of farmers to pull together their arms to defend their town to fight off the British - the most organized and armed army the world had seen at the time. You read the stories about how the town was burning and that is what called all the country folk to arms. But did it burn? If it did burn, was the fire started by American colonists themselves or the British? We'll never know the answer.

5/ Then, you go to brunch or lunch at the restaurant Fourth & Field down the road ~20 mins away, which is next to a small airport with a big window facing the airport. The food is basic American fare - nothing special - but you go to the restaurant to watch the planes take off, but really you go to watch the little kids rooting for the planes.

6/ If you really want you can go to Walden Pond and look at how goofy the cabin is. Seriously, this is a hilariously small cabin. You may comment on how commercial the place has gotten but just take a long walk around the perimeter of the pond and how commercial can a place really be if the walking paths have so much overgrowth?

---

These little kids love these planes and they cheer for them.

This airport restaurant is a beautiful place because it's the funniest thing in the world to watch little 3 - 6 year olds rooting for the planes coming in or taking off, and you laugh and smile at them and their parents, but it's seriously the funniest thing in the world to watch the excitement of little kids cheering on these little airplanes.

---

You can do the whole Concord, MA trip in about 5 hours and you'll live more in those few hours than you would watching Netflix or pretending to learn a new language on Duolingo.

Big fan of watching the little babies running around cheering for airplanes taking off and landing...

Big fan of all the humanity going on in the Concord, MA area...what a delight and what a joy to experience!

full_text:
If any of my little sparrows want to do some research 🇺🇸, try tracking all of the Shopify sites that:
a) Have $APP's Axon Pixel installed
b) Have CEOs/executives claiming that $APP didn't work for them

The $APP pixel is still embedded on many sites of companies who tried out $APP - so $APP is still leeching data off them.

For example, here is Jones Road Beauty.

Now, in a recent Marketing Brew article we see CEO @codyplof stating that $APP didn't work well for them and they pulled back spend late last year.

Yes as of today, $APP's still got a pixel embedded on the site, so $APP is "aware" of you if you're browsing on the site and purchasing things as it seems Jones Road didn't remove this.

This pixel is very critical. Because it's a custom pixel it can hide in some cases where Meta's pixel (much larger, more well known) can be picked up by ad blockers or other filters. Plus, many Shopify brands use the Meta Conversions API as their "source of truth" about customers rather than the Meta pixel because the Meta pixel is so blocked. It's important because the Conversions API fires at the point of purchase then "looks back" at the customer data, rather than a pixel, which registers earlier in the customer journey at the point of a customer landing on the site.

$APP benefits twice here.

One, if their pixel is not caught but Meta's pixel is, they can "front-run" Meta by quickly firing an ad once a landing page is reached but before a purchase is made, which fires Meta's Conversions API.

Two, if $APP's customers are lazy and don't remove the pixel even after they may have decided $APP isn't for them, $APP's still on the site and able to get a picture of who is on the site. Very sloppy stuff.

Of course, most of $APP's ML and Axon team appears to be located in Mainland China, so all this data is going right to the PRC/CCP.
